05494nam a22008055i 9780691249339DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912493397 a10.1515/97806912493392doi  a(DE-B1597)649973  a(OCoLC)1372399822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHG243b.N35 2023 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a332.4/940902223/eng/202307171 aNaismith, Rory, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Money in the Early Middle Ages /cRory Naismith. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (540 p.) :b41 b/w illus. 1 table. 11 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustration -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tNote on Values -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tPart I. -- tChapter 2. Bullion, Mining, and Minting -- tChapter 3. Why Make Money? -- tChapter 4. Using Coined Money -- tChapter 5. Money, Metal, and Commodities -- tPart II. -- tChapter 6. The Roman Legacy -- tChapter 7. Continuity and Change in the Fifth to Seventh Centuries -- tChapter 8. The Rise of the Denarius c. 660–900 -- tChapter 9. Money and Power in the Tenth and Eleventh Centuries -- tChapter 10. Conclusion: A Sketch of Early Medieval Money -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn examination of coined money and its significance to rulers, aristocrats and peasants in early medieval EuropeBetween the end of the Roman Empire in the fifth century and the economic transformations of the twelfth, coined money in western Europe was scarce and high in value, difficult for the majority of the population to make use of. And yet, as Rory Naismith shows in this illuminating study, coined money was made and used throughout early medieval Europe. It was, he argues, a powerful tool for articulating people’s place in economic and social structures and an important gauge for levels of economic complexity. Working from the premise that using coined money carried special significance when there was less of it around, Naismith uses detailed case studies from the Mediterranean and northern Europe to propose a new reading of early medieval money as a point of contact between economic, social, and institutional history.Naismith examines structural issues, including the mining and circulation of metal and the use of bullion and other commodities as money, and then offers a chronological account of monetary development, discussing the post-Roman period of gold coinage, the rise of the silver penny in the seventh century and the reconfiguration of elite power in relation to coinage in the tenth and eleventh centuries. In the process, he counters the conventional view of early medieval currency as the domain only of elite gift-givers and intrepid long-distance traders. Even when there were few coins in circulation, Naismith argues, the ways they were used—to give gifts, to pay rents, to spend at markets—have much to tell us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCoinagezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aCoinage-Europe-History-To 1500. 0aEurope-Economic conditions-To 1492. 0aMiddle Ages. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aCoinage.  aCommerce.  aEconomy.  aEurope.  aGovernment.  aMedieval.  aMediterranean.  aMonetary.  aMoney.  aScandinavia.  aStates.  aTrade.  aVikings.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108